REF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 218<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 7:01:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   What if Alexander the Great's Empire didn't die with him?</span><hr size=1> PO post on a fictional hostile alien race makes me ponder this question. What if his empire survived his death and went on to conquer the world? Also, what if we should in the future encounter a species that relatively early in its history was united into a single empire by force? I think that it is likely that it would be hostile, and wish to subdue us. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 676<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/9/03 12:04:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if Alexander the Great's Empire didn't die with him</span><hr size=1> I think, as far as Alex the Great goes, the empire would have crumbled eventually.  I'm not terribly knowledgeable about his conquests, but from I gather, whenever he did conquer a land he'd pretty much move on and the conquered people would get back to doing things the way they pretty much had in the first place without much further interference.  If an alien race had united itself through force by their version of an Alexander the Great I think your right in that they might lack a lot of moral fortitude since the civilization wouldn't have had a lot of time to &quot;experiment&quot; with different political systems and develop philosophies that respect the rights of its individuals and the free flow of ideas.  I think it just depends on how democratic such a society would be but I doubt if it would be very democratic since a lot of dissenting cultures in the USSR and even the USA had to be suppressed at some time or another.     <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2853<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/9/03 8:08:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if Alexander the Great's Empire didn't die with him</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Sure, civilizations tend to become a bit more benevolent and &quot;wiser&quot; as time goes on <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
From another thread.<br>
<br>
I think we are almost exactly the same as our ancestors over a thousand years ago. If anything we have become more savage. Tribes once fought over available food and maybe women. I've seen a few pub brawls and I can tell you that most broken bottles stabbed into faces are over a woman. So we aren't all that much different. It's easy to say that only applies to yobbo's on alcohol but what about the thousands massacred in the Middle East over a black sludge we call oil. What about Kashmir. A worthless godforsaken wasteland at the heart of endless skirmishes between India and Pakistan. I wouldn't even take the place as a gift. How about the Japanese eating Dolphins and hacking other Dolphins to death for stealing 'their' fish? The way we in the West buy dogs and cats at Xmas time and they end up destroyed by the RSPCA before New Years eve? No. We've swapped swords for guns but we certainly aren't any wiser. Clever yes. Many of us can work a VCR and fill in a crossword puzzle, but wisdom is rare and often false. There are countless Guru's on every subject imaginable who have never been truly tested and never will be. The great wise men are all gone. Solomon, Leonardo Da Vinci, Archimedes, Musashi, Aristotle, Napolean Boneaparte, Alexander, Sun Tzu, Confucius, to name but a few. Wise men are visionaries unafraid of risking failure. Only a handful have existed in more recent times. Edison might be one. Wisdom does not equate to an aversion for war. Some of the wisest men who ever lived were warriors.  <br>
<br>
Democracy is a recent experiment not fully tested or trusted. In times of seriousness such as war, it is left in the garden to play and replaced by a dictatorship. The military takes over until easily manageable peace is restored and Democracy can once again be allowed inside. Past republics have crumbled and the entire system may one day be ascribed to the dustbin of history. It's too soon to tell for certain, but my gut feeling is that Democracy hasn't the survivability to endure. <br>
<br>
Our World is not united but others out there might be. If a land can be dominated by a single government then its logical to assume some regions of the Galaxy might have a single Government. Holding together such a farflung Empire would be difficult and I'm sorry to tell you best accomplished by a brutal dictatorship. Alexander knew that mercy was for the weak. Only fear keeps foreign nations in line. There will always be resistance and if it isn't stamped out it grows. I don't want to argue right or wrong. Thats just how it is. Most lands on Earth were created through bloodletting and domination. Therefore, the mightiest races in the Galaxy, atleast to my way of thinking, must be incredibly brutal conquerors. These types of civilisation would be likely to come out on top in any first contact. Every colony would be heavily patrolled to maintain control and the entire race would act as one.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 90<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/21/03 9:57:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if Alexander the Great's Empire didn't die with him</span><hr size=1> Dam, you have some depressing posts...<br>
